=== 9.2 The Math

A single transformer block (Pre-LN variant, used by most modern GPTs):

[stem]
++++
\begin{aligned}
x_1 &= x + \text{MHA}(\text{LayerNorm}(x)) && \text{(attention sub-layer)} \\
x_2 &= x_1 + \text{FFN}(\text{LayerNorm}(x_1)) && \text{(FFN sub-layer)}
\end{aligned}
++++

This is the *Pre-Layer-Norm* architecture.
The original "Attention Is All You Need" paper used Post-LN, but Pre-LN is more stable to train and is used in GPT-2 onwards.

==== Layer Normalization

For a vector stem:[x \in \mathbb{R}^d]:

[stem]
++++
\operatorname{LayerNorm}(x) = \gamma \odot \frac{x - \mu}{\sigma} + \beta
++++

where stem:[\mu = \tfrac{1}{d}\sum_i x_i], stem:[\sigma = \sqrt{\tfrac{1}{d}\sum_i (x_i - \mu)^2}], stem:[\gamma, \beta \in \mathbb{R}^d] are learned scale and shift, and stem:[\odot] is element-wise multiplication.

[NOTE]
====
*Math Minute — Variance and Standard Deviation*

The variance of a set of numbers stem:[\{x_1, \ldots, x_n\}] measures how spread out they are:
stem:[Var = (1/n) \sum_i (x_i - \mu)^2] where stem:[\mu] is the mean.
The standard deviation stem:[\sigma = \sqrt{Var}] is in the same units as the original values.
Dividing by stem:[\sigma] makes the spread equal to 1 — "standardizing."
====

=== 9.3 The Residual Stream

A powerful way to understand the GPT architecture is through the lens of the *residual stream* (Elhage et al., Anthropic 2021):

The input embedding is injected into a "stream" — a vector of dimension `d` per token.
Each transformer block *reads from* this stream (via attention and FFN) and *adds back to* it (via residual connections).
The stream carries information across all blocks.

----
stream⁰ = token_embeddings + positional_encodings    [T × d]
stream¹ = stream⁰ + MHA(LN(stream⁰))
stream¹ = stream¹ + FFN(LN(stream¹))
stream² = stream¹ + MHA(LN(stream¹))
stream² = stream² + FFN(LN(stream²))
  ⋮
streamᴺ = final output
----

This view clarifies that attention heads and FFN neurons are all writing to the same shared workspace.
